[result]: The literature generally finds that CBDCs could support inclusion where they reduce transaction costs, enable low-cost digital wallets, improve government-to-person payments, and provide safer payment rails. Risks center on bank deposit substitution, higher funding costs, possible disintermediation, faster digital bank runs, and uncertain effects on interest-rate pass-through depending on CBDC design.

{"tool":"propose","answer":"Central bank digital currencies could improve financial inclusion in emerging markets if they are designed as low-cost, widely accessible public payment instruments rather than as sophisticated digital assets for already banked users. Their strongest inclusion channel would be through basic wallets with minimal fees, offline functionality, interoperability with mobile money and bank accounts, and simplified but risk-based identity requirements. In countries where many households lack bank accounts but have mobile phones, a CBDC could make transfers, remittances, merchant payments, and government benefits cheaper and more reliable.\n\nThe inclusion gains are not automatic. A CBDC would need broad merchant acceptance, consumer trust, digital literacy, cybersecurity protections, and reliable telecommunications infrastructure. If access requires formal identification, smartphones, or stable internet, it may exclude the same rural, informal, and low-income groups it is meant to help. A two-tier model, where commercial banks and regulated payment firms distribute CBDC wallets under central bank oversight, may be more practical than a purely central-bank-operated system.\n\nThe main risk for commercial banks is deposit substitution. If households and firms shift balances from bank deposits into CBDC, banks could lose a cheap and stable source of funding, raising lending costs or reducing credit supply, especially for small firms. In stress periods, CBDC could also make bank runs faster because depositors could instantly move funds into a risk-free central bank liability. These risks can be limited through non-interest-bearing CBDC, holding caps, tiered remuneration, transaction limits, or designs that preserve the role of banks in customer relationships.\n\nFor monetary policy transmission, CBDCs have ambiguous effects. On one hand, a well-designed CBDC could strengthen transmission by increasing the reach of digital payments, improving the speed of transfers, and potentially giving central banks a more direct channel to households. On the other hand, if CBDC weakens bank balance sheets, reduces deposit funding, or destabilizes credit creation, traditional bank-lending channels could become less effective. Overall, CBDCs can support financial inclusion in emerging markets, but their benefits depend less on the technology itself than on design choices that balance access, privacy, banking-sector stability, and monetary control."}

